    "summary": "Guatemala's internal armed conflict lasted from 1960 to 1996, making it one of the longest civil wars in Latin American history. The conflict began with a failed military revolt against the government installed after the CIA-backed overthrow of elected president Jacobo Árbenz in 1954. It evolved into a protracted insurgency by left-wing guerrilla movements against a succession of military governments, which received substantial US support during the Cold War.\n\nThe war's most devastating phase occurred in the early 1980s under General Efraín Ríos Montt, when the military conducted a scorched-earth counterinsurgency campaign in highland indigenous Maya communities. A UN-sponsored truth commission later classified many of these operations as acts of genocide. An estimated 200,000 people were killed or disappeared during the conflict, with indigenous Maya communities bearing the brunt of state violence. Over a million people were displaced. The peace accords signed in December 1996 ended the fighting and established frameworks for indigenous rights and military accountability, though full implementation remained incomplete.",
